WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.091 --> 00:00:05.792
<v Daniel>Picture this. You've just spent a small fortune on this luxury houseboat vacation.</v>

2
00:00:06.012 --> 00:00:08.033
<v Maya>Oh man, I can already see where this is going.</v>

3
00:00:08.373 --> 00:00:15.895
<v Daniel>Right. So you arrive at this beautiful, pristine lake. But by day three, you are just utterly exhausted.</v>

4
00:00:15.955 --> 00:00:17.815
<v Maya>Yeah, you're practically doing manual labor.</v>

5
00:00:17.995 --> 00:00:25.857
<v Daniel>Exactly. You're spending your mornings hauling heavy groceries down these steep, slippery dirt banks. You're dragging luggage across docks.</v>

6
00:00:26.077 --> 00:00:28.238
<v Maya>It's like the opposite of a vacation.</v>

7
00:00:28.900 --> 00:00:36.903
<v Daniel>It really is. Every evening you're wrestling with heavy anchors just to secure the boat. And then on top of all that, you're cooking every single meal yourself.</v>

8
00:00:36.963 --> 00:00:37.223
<v Maya>Yeah.</v>

9
00:00:37.523 --> 00:00:46.086
<v Daniel>You paid for a premium getaway, but somehow you are doing intense physical labor on your own vacation. And I mean, why does this happen?</v>

10
00:00:46.266 --> 00:00:51.448
<v Maya>Well, it happens because the company that sold you that vacation didn't really know how to map the invisible.</v>

11
00:00:51.748 --> 00:01:00.001
<v Daniel>Which perfectly brings us to our mission for this deep dive today. We are decoding the invisible architecture of the services you interact with like every single day.</v>

12
00:01:00.421 --> 00:01:05.309
<v Maya>It's honestly one of the most common and frankly most expensive blind spots in modern business.</v>

13
00:01:05.728 --> 00:01:13.852
<v Daniel>For sure. Because we try to manage experiences and services using the exact same tools that we use to manage physical, tangible objects.</v>

14
00:01:13.932 --> 00:01:16.093
<v Maya>And that just completely breaks down. It doesn't work.</v>

15
00:01:16.233 --> 00:01:26.338
<v Daniel>So today we're looking at the fundamental physics of how services operate. We'll look at how massive corporations draw literal maps to manipulate your experience without you even realizing</v>

16
00:01:26.378 --> 00:01:26.438
it.

17
00:01:26.818 --> 00:01:33.541
<v Maya>Yeah. And finally, how those exact same maps are being used right now to teach artificial intelligence how to interact with human beings.</v>

18
00:01:33.987 --> 00:01:45.319
<v Daniel>It's fascinating. And to do this, we're pulling insights from this really great stack of research spanning the last 40 years. We've got foundational theories from a 1982 paper by G. Lynn Shostak.</v>

19
00:01:45.339 --> 00:01:46.180
<v Maya>Yeah, that's a classic.</v>

20
00:01:46.240 --> 00:01:56.551
<v Daniel>Then a 2008 practical guide by Bittner, Ostrom, and Morgan. And all the way up to a cutting-edge case study from 2023 by Magyari and Sekimandi on machine learning.</v>

21
00:01:57.082 --> 00:02:06.710
<v Maya>The evolution here is just wild. I mean, we're going to trace a direct line from the economics of like a corner shoeshine stand all the way to complex neural networks in modern hospitals.</v>

22
00:02:07.010 --> 00:02:16.217
<v Daniel>It's a huge journey. And for you listening, whether you're a manager trying to fix a broken customer experience or you just want to know why your favorite coffee shop operates the way it does.</v>

23
00:02:16.590 --> 00:02:24.637
<v Maya>Yeah, understanding this concept of service blueprinting is, well, it's the ultimate shortcut to seeing the matrix of the modern economy.</v>

24
00:02:24.898 --> 00:02:28.561
<v Daniel>OK, let's unpack this. We have to start with the physics of invisible things.</v>

25
00:02:28.681 --> 00:02:37.369
<v Maya>Right. Because to map a service, we first have to accept that a service fundamentally disobeys the laws of physics that govern physical products.</v>

26
00:02:37.669 --> 00:02:40.412
<v Daniel>Which is just laid out back in the early 80s.</v>

27
00:02:40.717 --> 00:02:50.945
<v Maya>Exactly. And the distinction really boils down to dimensions. So a physical product like a smartphone or a toaster, it exists in both time and space.</v>

28
00:02:50.965 --> 00:02:52.206
<v Daniel>You can hold it. You can weigh it.</v>

29
00:02:52.386 --> 00:02:59.632
<v Maya>Right. You can possess it. But a service exists exclusively in time. It cannot be possessed. It can only be rendered and experienced.</v>

30
00:02:59.652 --> 00:03:01.994
<v Daniel>Because it only exists in time. It's inherently fleeting.</v>

31
00:03:02.074 --> 00:03:02.294
<v Maya>Right.</v>

32
00:03:02.474 --> 00:03:04.936
<v Daniel>I mean, you can't put a haircut on a shelf and just save it for later.</v>

33
00:03:05.196 --> 00:03:11.701
<v Maya>That is the crucial constraint. So think of a service as being kind of like electricity. It exists in two completely different states.</v>

34
00:03:11.961 --> 00:03:13.742
<v Daniel>Like potential and kinetic energy.</v>

35
00:03:14.022 --> 00:03:28.772
<v Maya>Exactly. Let's use your barber example. When that trained barber is just sitting in an empty shop reading a magazine, they represent potential energy. They possess this stored capability to cut hair, but nothing is actually happening. The</v>

36
00:03:28.872 --> 00:03:32.555
<v Maya>actual haircut, the service itself, is kinetic energy.</v>

37
00:03:32.760 --> 00:03:37.121
<v Daniel>Got it. So it only exists while it is in motion, while the shears are moving and the hair is falling.</v>

38
00:03:37.181 --> 00:03:45.643
<v Maya>Right. But in the real world, most of the things we buy aren't purely one or the other. You know, we rarely buy just pure potential energy or pure kinetic energy.</v>

39
00:03:45.943 --> 00:03:49.124
<v Daniel>That brings us to what Shostak called the molecular model, right?</v>

40
00:03:49.144 --> 00:03:56.065
<v Maya>Yeah. Market entities are almost always these combinations of products and services linked together like atoms in a molecule.</v>

41
00:03:56.366 --> 00:03:58.866
<v Daniel>So like table salt would be a pure product atom.</v>

42
00:03:59.046 --> 00:04:10.075
<v Maya>Exactly. There's virtually no service attached to a box of salt. But look at a car. A car is a massive product atom, but it's fundamentally bound to the service atom of transportation.</v>

43
00:04:10.556 --> 00:04:13.619
<v Daniel>And if you swing to the far other end of the spectrum.</v>

44
00:04:13.880 --> 00:04:23.891
<v Maya>Then you have something like an amusement park. An amusement park is almost entirely a kinetic service with maybe like a few minor product atoms thrown in.</v>

45
00:04:24.367 --> 00:04:26.688
<v Daniel>Like a plastic souvenir cup or a hot dog or whatever.</v>

46
00:04:26.728 --> 00:04:27.828
<v Maya>Yeah, exactly. I</v>

47
00:04:27.908 --> 00:04:37.691
<v Daniel>love looking at it as a chemistry set for businesses. Because if you alter just one atom in that molecule, you fundamentally change the reality of what you're selling.</v>

48
00:04:37.711 --> 00:04:38.291
<v Maya>Oh, for sure.</v>

49
00:04:38.411 --> 00:04:47.073
<v Daniel>Like if you take the transportation service atom away from that car, it just ceases to be a vehicle. It becomes like a museum piece, a sculpture.</v>

50
00:04:47.273 --> 00:04:56.375
<v Maya>And because those kinetic atoms, the service parts, are invisible and intangible, they desperately rely on physical proxies to make them feel real to the consumer.</v>

51
00:04:56.575 --> 00:04:58.395
<v Daniel>Which is what Shostak calls evidence.</v>

52
00:04:58.515 --> 00:05:04.896
<v Maya>Right. And there are two kinds. So peripheral evidence is something like an airline ticket or a receipt. The ticket isn't the flight itself, right?</v>

53
00:05:04.916 --> 00:05:06.617
<v Daniel>No, it just confirms that the service exists.</v>

54
00:05:06.797 --> 00:05:14.438
<v Maya>Exactly. But then there's essential evidence. Essential evidence actually facilitates the service and it completely dictates your psychological trust in it.</v>

55
00:05:14.810 --> 00:05:17.354
<v Daniel>So the airplane itself would be essential evidence.</v>

56
00:05:17.555 --> 00:05:27.030
<v Maya>The airplane, the cleanliness of the tray table, the pilot's uniform. I mean, think about it. You wouldn't trust a surgeon who walks into the operating room wearing muddy boots and a torn T-shirt.</v>

57
00:05:27.651 --> 00:05:28.353
<v Daniel>Definitely not.</v>

58
00:05:28.741 --> 00:05:41.112
<v Maya>Even if their kinetic skill, their actual surgical ability is world class, the essential evidence fails. The tangible evidence heavily manipulates how we perceive that intangible experience.</v>

59
00:05:41.352 --> 00:05:53.023
<v Daniel>OK, let me push back on this a little bit, though. If a service is kinetic and it's always in motion, like that haircut or that surgery, how can a business possibly standardize it without just stripping away the humanity?</v>

60
00:05:53.203 --> 00:05:54.386
<v Maya>That's the big challenge.</v>

61
00:05:54.446 --> 00:06:03.665
<v Daniel>Right. Because you could put a toaster on an assembly line and guarantee every toaster is identical. But you can't mass produce a haircut. Humans are messy, unpredictable variables.</v>

62
00:06:04.051 --> 00:06:10.194
<v Maya>That unpredictability is exactly why the earliest service models introduced this concept of deviation tolerances.</v>

63
00:06:10.334 --> 00:06:11.295
<v Daniel>Deviation tolerances.</v>

64
00:06:11.315 --> 00:06:26.282
<v Maya>Yeah. So every service has an engineered ideal blueprint, but it also has a built-in tolerance for deviation. Let's look at a simple street corner shoeshine. The standard engineered blueprint for that shoeshine might dictate that the process should take</v>

65
00:06:26.382 --> 00:06:31.784
<v Maya>exactly two minutes now as a consumer your tolerance might stretch up to five minutes</v>

66
00:06:31.844 --> 00:06:34.544
<v Daniel>so if i'm sitting there for four minutes i'm still perfectly happy</v>

67
00:06:34.684 --> 00:06:42.886
<v Maya>right the kinetic energy feels fine to you but beyond five minutes your perceived quality of the service plummets you start checking your watch</v>

68
00:06:43.146 --> 00:06:48.967
<v Daniel>so the business has a nice comfortable three minute buffer to play with where the customer is still happy right</v>

69
00:06:49.239 --> 00:06:51.803
<v Maya>Well, see, that is the trap most businesses fall into.</v>

70
00:06:52.003 --> 00:06:52.744
<v Daniel>Wait, really?</v>

71
00:06:52.784 --> 00:07:07.465
<v Maya>Yeah. They think the buffer belongs to the customer. But remember, for the business, the raw material of a service is time. Oh, wow. At two minutes, the shoeshine operator makes, let's say, a 20-cent profit margin. But if the shine drags on to four</v>

72
00:07:07.525 --> 00:07:11.289
<v Maya>minutes, the cost of that extra labor and time eats the margin entirely.</v>

73
00:07:11.349 --> 00:07:12.370
<v Daniel>So the profit drops to zero.</v>

74
00:07:12.590 --> 00:07:21.940
<v Maya>Exactly. The customer thinks everything is completely fine at four minutes. But internally, the business is literally losing money on every single shoe they shine.</v>

75
00:07:22.354 --> 00:07:34.720
<v Daniel>Wow. So the blueprint isn't just about making sure the customer smiles. It's this highly sensitive mathematical balance between the customer's patience and the provider's internal profitability.</v>

76
00:07:34.840 --> 00:07:39.583
<v Maya>Yes. The customer's tolerance and the profit tolerance are totally different metrics.</v>

77
00:07:39.833 --> 00:07:49.557
<v Daniel>And once businesses started to realize that these invisible kinetic events had such strict, unforgiving profit margins, I imagine they realized they couldn't just wing it anymore.</v>

78
00:07:49.697 --> 00:07:52.818
<v Maya>No, they needed a literal map to track this energy.</v>

79
00:07:52.979 --> 00:08:01.182
<v Daniel>Which moves us from the theoretical physics of the 80s into the practical tools of the 2000s. Yeah. We're talking about the evolution into the modern service blueprint.</v>

80
00:08:01.329 --> 00:08:08.117
<v Maya>Right. So the 2008 paper, the modern blueprint takes all of that kinetic energy and standardizes it across five core components.</v>

81
00:08:08.137 --> 00:08:09.038
<v Daniel>Break those down for us.</v>

82
00:08:09.138 --> 00:08:19.610
<v Maya>Sure. You map out the customer actions, the onstage or visible employee actions, the backstage or invisible employee actions, the support processes, and finally, that physical evidence we talked about earlier.</v>

83
00:08:19.945 --> 00:08:30.153
<v Daniel>I want to focus on how this is actually drawn because the structure of it is so fascinating. It relies heavily on these rigid boundaries. They call lines.</v>

84
00:08:30.353 --> 00:08:37.698
<v Maya>The lines are the secret sauce, really. Imagine drawing a map of a coffee shop on a whiteboard. At the top, you have the line of interaction.</v>

85
00:08:37.738 --> 00:08:41.481
<v Daniel>That's where the customer directly touches the business, right? Like ordering at the register.</v>

86
00:08:41.501 --> 00:08:46.405
<v Maya>Exactly. And just below that is the most crucial boundary, which is the line of visibility.</v>

87
00:08:47.050 --> 00:08:50.192
<v Daniel>Okay, so everything above that line is seen by the customer.</v>

88
00:08:50.352 --> 00:08:57.917
<v Maya>Yeah, the barista steaming the milk, the pastry display, the music playing. Everything below it is completely invisible to them.</v>

89
00:08:58.017 --> 00:08:58.538
<v Daniel>And below that?</v>

90
00:08:58.798 --> 00:09:11.186
<v Maya>Below that, you have the line of internal interaction. That separates the frontline staff from back-end support, like the person in the back room roasting the coffee beans or the payroll software.</v>

91
00:09:11.386 --> 00:09:13.988
<v Daniel>It basically operates entirely like a theater production.</v>

92
00:09:14.229 --> 00:09:15.790
<v Maya>Yes, that's a perfect analogy.</v>

93
00:09:15.971 --> 00:09:24.158
<v Daniel>The customer is the audience and they only see the actors on stage. But those actors look like fools if the stagehands backstage aren't pulling the ropes.</v>

94
00:09:24.578 --> 00:09:31.204
<v Maya>Right. And none of them can function without the lighting grid and the power supply, which are the support processes deep in the basement.</v>

95
00:09:31.604 --> 00:09:38.851
<v Daniel>And seeing those lines on a piece of paper can radically alter how a company operates. Let's look at that yellow transportation example from the paper.</v>

96
00:09:39.118 --> 00:09:50.582
<v Maya>Oh, that's such a good case study. They were a massive trucking and logistics company. Back in 1997, they were literally scraping the bottom of Fortune's least admired companies list. Ouch.</v>

97
00:09:50.982 --> 00:09:52.243
<v Daniel>So they were really struggling.</v>

98
00:09:52.323 --> 00:09:57.624
<v Maya>Very much so. So they sat down and mapped out their core delivery service using a blueprint.</v>

99
00:09:58.085 --> 00:10:02.586
<v Daniel>What did the map show them that they couldn't already see? I mean, they're a trucking company.</v>

100
00:10:03.386 --> 00:10:12.730
<v Maya>It showed them their true face. The executives probably assumed their brand was their corporate logo or their expensive sales team. But when they drew the line of interaction, they</v>

101
