102
00:10:14.331 --> 00:10:29.295
<v Maya>Exactly. They realized the only people constantly crossing that line were their unionized Teamster truck drivers. The driver backing the rig into the loading dock, handing over the clipboard, making small talk with the warehouse manager. That driver was the primary onstage</v>

103
00:10:29.455 --> 00:10:29.735
<v Maya>actor.</v>

104
00:10:30.207 --> 00:10:40.868
<v Daniel>So the executives were pouring money into things below the line of visibility when the entire customer experience was happening above the line in the cab of an 18-wheeler.</v>

105
00:10:41.220 --> 00:10:50.884
<v Maya>The blueprint made it undeniably clear. So Yellow Transportation pivoted hard. They shifted their entire operational strategy to support those drivers.</v>

106
00:10:51.084 --> 00:10:52.885
<v Daniel>They upgraded the technology in the cabs, right? Yep,</v>

107
00:10:53.005 --> 00:11:05.671
<v Maya>revamped their training to focus on customer interaction and treated the drivers as the core brand ambassadors. That shift, driven entirely by seeing that line of visibility, helped take them from worst to first in their industry.</v>

108
00:11:05.831 --> 00:11:09.793
<v Daniel>That's incredible. But what happens if you don't have a backstage at all?</v>

109
00:11:10.333 --> 00:11:10.733
<v Maya>What do you mean?</v>

110
00:11:11.473 --> 00:11:23.558
